        <h2 class="title"><a href="/solar-economics-spreadsheet">A solar economics spreadsheet</a></h2>    <span class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Sun, 2007-02-25 01:09.</span>
    <span class="taxonomy"><ul class="links inline"><li class="first taxonomy_term_44"><a href="/taxonomy/term/44" rel="tag" title="Environmental issues" class="taxonomy_term_44">Going Green</a></li>
<li class="last taxonomy_term_49"><a href="/tags/solar" rel="tag" title="" class="taxonomy_term_49">solar</a></li>
</ul></span>
    <div class="content"><p>In light of my recent threads on <a href="http://ideas.4brad.com/citizenre-real-or-imagined-challenge">CitizenRe</a> I built a <a href="http://www.templetons.com/tech/solar.xls">spreadsheet to do solar energy economic calculations</a>.  If you click on that, you can download the spreadsheet to try for yourself.   If you don&#8217;t have a spreadsheet program (I recommend the free Gnumeric or Open Office) it&#8217;s also up as a <a href="http://spreadsheets.google.com/ccc?key=pWKShknjJFBt7sOTCJre_SQ">Google Solar Spreadsheet</a> but you may need a Google account to plug in your own numbers. <span class='read-more'><a href="http://ideas.4brad.com/solar-economics-spreadsheet">&nbsp;read&nbsp;more&nbsp;&raquo;</a></span></p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links inline"><li class="first blog_usernames_blog"><a href="/blog/brad" title="Read brad&#039;s latest blog entries." class="blog_usernames_blog">brad&#039;s blog</a></li>
